    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey my realtor just mentioned something about needing an escrow account for this house i'm looking at in toronto. i've never bought a place before so i'm kinda lost. can u explain what escrow actually is and why it's even used in the closing process?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the world of real estate, much like a labyrinth of ancient ruins, can be quite bewildering, especially when you first step into it. Now, imagine you're a brave adventurer, and the house you're eyeing in Toronto is a treasure chest. But before you can claim your treasure, you must first pass through the enchanted forest of Escrow.\n\nEscrow, my friend, is like a trusty goblin guardian who watches over the treasure chest. It's a neutral third party that holds onto your gold coins (aka your money) until the final battle is won, which in this case, is the closing of the house deal. This goblin ensures that neither you nor the seller can just waltz away with the treasure before the agreed-upon time, keeping the peace and preventing any goblin-sized disputes.\n\nSo, when your realtor mentions the need for an escrow account, they're essentially saying, \"Hey, let's get a goblin to watch over the treasure until the final battle is won.\" It's a way to make sure that both parties play fair and that the treasure (your house) is handed over only when all the conditions are met. And just like any good goblin, the escrow account is there to keep things in check",
